review_blob: Color of stained pine. Smells of fresh cut pine. Tastes like PineSol. Seriously guys, how much pine can you cram into one beer?

Almost black with virtually no head to speak of. Roasted malt, coffee, dark chocolate, vanilla and smoke with a slight peppery finish. A tad on the sweet side and heavy on the chocolate, but otherwise almost perfect.
Almost black with a nice brown head. Plenty of lacing. Espresso, licorice, cedar, amaretto and rum. Very complex. The ABV packs a punch.
Very deep brown with minimal head and some lacing. Smell is grassy hops, caramel malt and alcohol. Taste is primarily of bakers chocolate, espresso, molasses and licorice.
beer_name: Clown Shoes The Good, The Bad & The Unidragon

review_blob: Light golden with a thin white head, some lacing. Highly carbonated. Hoppy, crisp finish. Grassy and floral. A little soapy. Not impressive but pleasant.
Almost black with a thin tan head, some lacing. Smell is mostly chocolate. Taste is mostly espresso with a smoky finish. Balanced and smooth though a bit oily. An impressive Porter.
Hazy copper colored with no head. Smells of pine and biscuit. Taste is slightly sweet with caramel malt and plenty of grassy hops on the finish. A decent brew but a little boring.
Clear copper colored with a moderate head. Plenty of carbonation. Nicely balanced with caramel malt and a subtle hop profile. A tad on the dry side for the style but still good and highly drinkable.
Dark brown, with no head or lacing. Woody with sour apple and high on the alcohol notes. A weird spicy note...almost dill. Not very pleasant.
beer_name: Ranger Creek Texas Bourbon Barrel Imperial Brown Ale

review_blob: Dark cola colored with thin tan head and minimal lacing. Smells of raisin, leather and licorice. Taste is heavily roasted malt and coffee with a smokey finish. A bit on the dry side for my tastes.
Clear copper with a moderate white head. Fairly carbonated. Minimal lacing. Grain, malt, fruity hops. Slightly spicy finish. A pretty nice representation of the style.
Pale straw colored, thin white head, some lacing. Slightly floral and peppery. A bit heavy on the cereal grain for a Pils. Not bad, just not a great example of the style.
Light copper, highly carbonated but no head. Tastes like Shiner Blonde with a spritz of grapefruit juice. I find it to be a bit offputting, but then again, I never like fruit beers.
Pale straw color with a medium white head. Tastes a like a wheat beer to me. Grain, malt, minimal hops. A tittle tart on the finish. An ok lawnmower beer, but nothing special.
Clear golden, highly carbonated, thin white head, some lacing. Malty with a hint of grassy hops. Slight floral note. Things you expect in a Pils, but subdued. Pleasant enough, but a little bland.

Pale hazy light golden with a thin head. Some lacing. Pine and Lemon Peel. A bit floral. Very dry with absolutely no malt to be found. Watery and one sided. A weak IPA.

Dark coffee colored. Unfortunately, no head to speak of. Mouthfeel is a bit flat. Now, Im done complaining, because the beer tastes great! Bittersweet chocolate with slight coffee notes, a hint of vanilla and a slight peppery spiciness. A delicious balanced chocolate stout that isnt too sweet. The spiciness adds an interesting dimension. It was also priced competitively, so I will be adding this one to the rotation.

Dark cola colored with a nice mocha head, plenty of lacing. Very dark roasted coffee, like Charbucks style. Roasted malt and licorice. A bit bread like on the finish. Interesting but too much bite from the charred coffee for my taste.
A light copper with a thin white head and no lacing. Very malty and a bit sweet. Grassy and grainy with a crisp finish. Nicely balanced.
Crystal clear light golden with a thin white head and plenty of lacing. Highly carbonated. A little tart and acidic. Tastes grassy and floral. Very balanced and quite pleasant.
Clear copper color. Minimal lacing or head. Mostly caramel malt. A bit bready. A tad bitter on the finish. Overall a pleasant and balanced brew.

Pours a nice deep chocolate brown with an impressive nut colored head. Thats it for the compliments. This thing really tastes like a birthday cake, which is fine for a birthday cake, but not a beer. The smell is seriously that of one of those sheet cakes bought at Walmart. Taste is that of a dry stout that has had chocolate cake mix, vanilla frosting and sprinkles poured in. No thanks.

Pours a crystal clear golden with a thick foamy white head. Decent lacing. Smells of lemon and grass. Tastes of the same plus bread and malt with floral notes on the finish. A very fine, well balanced Pilsener.

Slightly hazy straw color with a nice foamy white head. Highly carbonated. Its an IPA alright. Prominent hop bite, but not as overpowering as some. Grapefruit, pine. Its a bit more fruity and tart than expected. Decent malty finish making it more balanced than expected.

Packaged in an impressive corked bottle. Deep brown with a thick ivory head. Plenty of lacing. Very malty with a slight hop bite on the finish. Very balanced. Fruity with hints of plum and raisin. Quite a kick at 10% ABV the alcohol is not overly present in the aroma or taste.
12.26.14 Batch - Heavy on the pine. Floral. Citrus peel. Particularly dry for the style but also not of the charts with IBU. Fairly balanced.
Black as night, virtually no head or lacing. Smells of molasses. Tastes of heavily roasted malt and coffee with molasses. Quite a fine Imperial Stout.

A Thanksgiving treat for myself with my smoked turkey. Pours a hazy marmalade with a thin white head. Pine and Peppermint balanced with Caramel Malt. Its very hoppy for sure, but still quite balanced.

Nitro Can, poured with a thick foamy head, tons of lacing. Copper colored with a flowing carbonation from the nitro. Caramel Malt. Smooth, creamy, a little sweet and slight hop bite to the finish. It is a very drinkable and balanced brew as a Scottish Ale should be.

Light copper in color, thin head, some lacing. Sweet caramel malt up front with a dry finish. A little grassy and floral. It is similar to a pilsner but with more malt and a faint spiciness. Take my Native Texan card if you must, but I am not a big fan of most Shiner offerings. However, this is one of their better ones.

As with all Nitro Can Stouts, this one gets full points for appearance. Like its identical twin (Guinness) its creamy and balanced, but lacking in any real complexity. Theres Roasted Malt, a hint of coffee the faintest hint of hops and a slightly smokey finish. Exactly what I would expect in a mass produced Dry Stout and as such, I would prefer a good Imperial when I can get one.

Dark chocolate brown with a thick foamy tan head. Coffee and chocolate are prominent. Smokey finish. A tad hoppy for a stout and slightly lacking in malt profile, but that actually makes it kinda interesting. The alcohol is a bit prevalent. Still, a pretty decent stout all around.

beer_brewer_name: Magic Hat Brewing Company (North American Breweries)
review_blob: Dark cola colored, minimal head or lacing. The label and name is the best part with this one (Wilhelm Scream...that yelp you hear in every movie when some expendable character dies). Back on to the beer. Slightly malty, with an earthiness that is a bit overbearing. It has that vegetable overtone that reminds me of a New Belgium offering. Meh.
beer_name: Magic Hat Wilhelm Scream Pumpkin Ale

review_blob: Deep amber hue. Thin head. Like any Blue Moon offering (an Im not a fan) it is unimpressive. It has the adjunct macro taste of a MillerCoors beer with the label and price of a pseudo-craft. Very minimal hint of caramel malts with the expected pumpkin spice added in...presumably as a syrup latein the brewing process.
beer_name: Blue Moon Harvest Moon Pumpkin Ale

review_blob: Hazy deep copper with zero head. So much so that I wondered if it was flat, but there is some carbonation there. Tastes pretty much like a macro lager with a hint of cinnamon, ginger and allspice. No interesting malt or hop profile whatsoever. Disappointing.
Hazy amber. Thick foamy head. Plenty of lacing. Wheat, Rye, Citrus Zest and Pepper. Dry finish. It reminds me of a Belgian Wit but more complex and...well...better.
Hmm, Pumpkin Pie in a bottle. Malty, sweet, nutmeg, clove, etc. A pleasant and unique treat, but not something I would drink often.
Clear medium copper with a thin white head and plenty of lacing. Grassy and floral with pineapple and an almost minty finish. I like the uniqueness of this one.
beer_name: Samuel Adams Latitude 48 Deconstructed IPA - Mosaic

review_blob: Clear bronze, thin pale head, plenty of lacing. Pine and apricot. Earthy on the finish. Quite dry and not particularly hoppy. As others have said, doesnt actually taste much like an IPA.
beer_name: Samuel Adams Latitude 48 Deconstructed IPA - East Kent Goldings
